{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn83045217/00295860728/1921013001/0219.xml":{"full_text":"PRIY OF TE FILLS\nJ- H. Bixler returned Saturday from\ntf two weeks* visit in Seattle.\nF. L. Carey returned Saturday from\n\u00e4 short business trip to Missoula.\nWanted \u2014Auto to fill car shipping\nm Loa Angeles. Phone 9474.\u2014Adv.\nS. B. Jones of Qeyser was in Great\nFalls Saturday transacting business.\nFrank Levandosky of Fife was a\nbusiness viator in Great Falls Satur\nday.\n_ Mr. and Mrs. W. G. Blomqnist were\nVisitors in Great Falls Saturday from\nBelt\n\u201eMr. and Mrs. W. H. Scott were\nvisitors in Great Falls Saturday from\nBrady.\nE. Grindle returned Saturday after\nnoon from a few days' business visit\nat Butte,\n5>f. Barth, specializing in pyorrhea\n\u2022>nd extracting. Thisted block. Phone\n4622.\u2014Adv.\nMiss Nanna Swenson came in from\nSimms Saturday for a week end visit\nin Great Falls.\nE. E. Sweitser, an attorney at\nBrady, was a business visitor in Great\nFalls Saturday.\nWilliam H. Boyle came in from\nSwift Saturday for a short business\nvisit in Great Falls.\nMiss Marie Boyd of Hobson re\nturned home Saturday after a brief\ntrip to Great Falls.\nMiss Anna B. Lundgren came in\nfrom Conrad Saturday for a few days'\nf business visit here.\nJ.E. Kulstad came in from Mon\ntague Saturday for a brief business\nvisit in Great Falls.\nF. J. Lach came in from Dutton\nSaturday for a few days' business\nviBit in Great Falls.\nWanted Stenographer, who also\nhas general office experience. Apply\nP. O. box 1678.\u2014 Adr.\nMrs. B. A. Robertson returned \"to\nSun River Saturday after a brief shop\nping visit in Great Falls.\nMiss Edith Lilliefors returned to her\nhome at Vaughn Saturday after a\nshort visit in Great Falls.\nMiss Lorene Qualley left for Cas\ncade Saturday afternoon to spend the\nweek end with her parents.\nMiss Mary Longmuir arrived in\nGreat Falls Saturday morning from\nBrowning for the week end.\nG. W. Tintinger of Cascade was\namong the out-of-town business visi\ntors in Great Falls Saturday.\nH. Skogen arrived in Great Falls\nSaturday from Helena to spend the\nweek end with his wife and family.\nD. J. Crimmons of Seattle is spend\ning a few days in Great Falls and\nvicinity looking after ranch interests.\nMiss L. Messenger came in from\nAugusta Saturday for a brief visit re\nturning home on the afternoon train.\nMrs. George W. Stuffel returned to\nher home at Belt Saturday afternoon\nafter a brief shopping visit in Great\nFalls.\nMiss Vivian Bruneau, who is teach\ning school in the Deep Creek country,\nwas in Great Falls Saturday visiting\nfriends.\nH. B. McNair came in from Helena\nSaturday to spend a few days in\nGreat Falls looking after mercantile\ninterests here.\nMrs. Domonick Cinotto and son and\ndaughter returned to Lehigh Saturday\nafternoon after a brief shopping visit\nin Great Falls.\nMiss Sadie Witsier of Butte-snd who\nhas been spending several weeks with\nher mother, Mrs. Minnie Seifred at\nGeyser, returned to Geyser Saturday\nafter a few days' visit here with her\nsister-in-law, Mrs. W. A. Witsier.\nEvery Member of the\nFamily Likes Candy\nWhy not take home a box of our\ndelicious homemade candies next time\nyou pass our way?\nEvery one likes good pure candy like\nours.\nChocolate Shop\nRUSSELL BLOCK\n2 FIFTH STREET NORTH\nStylish Boots\nand Oxfords\nm\ny...'\ny.V'/V\nE take pleasure in inviting your inspec\ntion of the boots and low cut footwear\nwe have just received.\nThey were manufactured for us by JOHN\nKELLY, INC., the famous Rochester builders of\n\"Better Shoes.''\nShoes from JOHN KELLY are unexcelled in\nstyle, fitting and inherent value. They are made\nto conform to a quality standard that has been\nconsistently maintained for two generations.\nPfister-Pierce\nBootery\n409 Central Avenue\n-J.- r\nMiss Stella Holmberg left Sattirday\nafternoon for Belt for a two weeks\nvisit with her parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nJohn Kolmberg.\nMiss Heien Hart arrived to Great\nFalls Saturday from Butte for a visit\nwith Miss Elsie Steck while on her\nway to Kalispell.\nFrank E. McDonnell, Equitable life.\nN. Y., Real Estate, Bonds, Insurance.\n811 First National Bank building.\nFone 9591.\u2014Adv.\nMr. and Mrs. H. O. Woare were\nvisitors in Great Fallg Saturday from\nChester. Mr. Woare is a newspaper\nman at Chester.\nOne lot of taffeta hats reduced to\n$5 00 each. South Side Millinery, 115\n4th St. So., between 1st and 2nd Ave\nnues south.\u2014 Adv.\nMr. and Mrs. A. J. Nickerson of\nStanford were in Great Falls Saturday\nto visit their son, Jesse, who is ill\nat the Columbus hospital.\nHelen C Chapter, O. E. S., card\nparty Monday evening, January 31 for\nKastern Stars, Masons and families.\nAdmission 35 cents.\u2014Adv.\nMrs. Bernadine Kropp and eon Fred\nafter a brief shopping visit in Great\nFalls, returned to their home at Sun\nRiver Saturday afternoon.\nJ. F. Beckett, traveling passenger\nagent for the Great Northern railway\nhere, returned Saturday from a busi\nness trip in eastern Montana.\nMiss Clara Harner who is teaching\nschool at Dutton passed through Great\nFalls Saturday returning to Belt for a\nweek end visit with her parents.\nG. W. Massey returned Saturday\nfrom a business trip in the western\npart of the state in the interests of\nthe Equity Co-operative association.\nMrs. James Sulgrove returned to\nCboteau Saturday afternoon. Mrs.\nSulgrove has been a patient at the\nDeaconess hospital in Great Falls for\nthe last five weeks.\nMrs. John Temby and daughter, Miss\nJane Temby, of Chicago are in Great\nFalls for a few weeks' visit with their\ndaughters and sisters, Mrs. T. C.\nFerris and Miss Grace Temby.\nO. S. Forsythe, a member of the\nboard of directors of the Equity Co\noperative association, returned to\nFarmington Saturday after a few\ndays' business visit in Great Falls.\nMiss Harriet and Miss Alma Larson\nof Choteau were in Great Falls Sat\nurday for a brief visit while en route\nto Helena to spend the week end with\ntheir parents, Mr. and Mrs. T. O.\nLarson.\nMrs. E. H. Beardsley of 2301 First\navenue north was hostess Friday af\nternoon to 10 guests at an informal\nafternoon party. The afternoon was\nspent in fancy work and refreshments\nwere served.\nRichard Money of New York, who\nis press agent for \"The Greenwich\nVillage Follies,\" spent a few days in\nGreat Falls this week visiting his\naunt, Mrs. William Elliott, 1416 Fifth\navenue north.\nMrs. Anna Kantola passed through\nGreat Falls Saturday returning to\nSand Coulee from Salem where she\nspent a short time looking after ranch\ninterests. While in Great Falls she\nvisited her daughter, Miss Martha\nKantola.\nMrs. A. H. Reser of Chinook, who\nhas been in Great Falls for a few days\nvisiting her sister, Mrs. H. J. Thaxter,\nleft Saturday afternoon accompanied\nby Mrs. Thaxter for Raynesford to\nvisit Mrs. Thaxter's sons, Walter and\nRoy Fish.\nMrs. J. M. Hurley and children,\nLoretta, James, Joseph, Dolores,\nDavid, John and Mary left Saturday\nfor Spokane where they will join Mr.\nHurley and make their home. Mr.\nHurley was formerly superintendent of\nthe Great Northern shops and was\ntransferred to Spokane about a month\nago. Mr. and Mrs. Hurley and chil\ndren came to Great Falls last April\nfrom Havre.\nzr\nmm\nMailorders\nAre always received with the same object in\nview as that with which we serve our patrons\npersonally. To please, serve promptly and have\nthe pelasure gf serving often.\nI\n:4\nTHE BIG STORE\nImportant Shoe News\nIs contained on the opposite page. Do not over\nlook this January Clearance of Shoes, \"^hol\u00ae\nfamilies will be outfitted at a cost only slightly\nabove the former price for one pair of shoes.\nThis Is the Time for\n100% Optimism\nConditions everywhere point to a period of real\nprosperity.\nFactories now can produce goods at lower costs.\nPeople can buy practically everything cheaper than\nthey could for five years.\nThe business outlook is encouraging. There is rea\nson for everybody's feeling enthusiastic.\nThis is the time to dismiss all doubt\u2014to banish all\nuncertainty\u2014to think and talk in terms of optimism.\nThe future is bright. Everybody is settling down\nto work CHEERFULLY for normal prosperous times.\nSmiles and good cheer are catching. Optimism has\na reassuring strengthening influence.\nThe tonic of universal optimism is all the country\nneeds to keep prosperity going full speed ahead.\nSTRAIN BROTHERS.\nV.\nJ\nSilks\nWith the month of February fast approaching, the dawn\nof early spring turns women's thoughts to new frocks of\ndainty silks and satins. Here, then, is an early offering of\na few choice dress materials that should inspire deft hands.\n36-Inch Satin Etoile (or Instance\nIs a soft, billowy, clinging satin fabric quite charming for\nevening or practical for street wear. The complete show\ning of new shades for spring is enhanced by the presence of\na few striking, if not vivid shades. The price \u0152O OK\nis, the yard\nTaffeta Silks Again\n\u2014yes, and perhaps you're thinking \"always for me.\" When\nMilady finds a silk more pleasing than \"taffeta\" it will\ndoubtless be \"more taffeta.\" For immediate wear, there\nis a goodly supply of different shades, 36 inches wide and at\nsuch rock-bottom TO\nprices as\nImported English Madras Shirtings\nStill maintain their popularity for both women's and men's\nwear. These have a woven stripe and come in attractive\ncolorings. 32 inches wide. Priced, the\nyard\n75c\n\u2022\u2014Silk Section, Main Floor.\nNot to Obscure\u2014but to\nEnhance Milady's Beauty\n-Is the Veil\nIt matters not whether you prefer a Diamond, Hexagon or\nShetland mesh veil, the fact remains; one just must have a\nveil these windy days, if one is to appear debonair.\nA touch of gay color has been added with silk designs here\nand there.\nPrices are,\neach\n75c\u2122 $3.50\n-Main Floor.\nIs the Trend Today\nAnnnouncing Plume\nBrand Lingerie' for\nSpring\nSo many inquiries have reached us indirectly\nabout Plume Brand Undergarments, we have taken\nthis opportunity to announce and impress upon our\nwomen patrons the fact that Plume Brandy Under\ngarments are sold exclusively at this store, in Great\nFalls.\nPlume Brand Undergarments are the embodiment\nof latest styles, cotton materials of the highest\nNight Gowns\nEnvelope Chemise\nPajamas\nUnderskirts\nBloomers\n\nquality, good workmanship and fair prices. Well\ndressed women who prefer muslin undergarments\nof a kind 'just a little better than the rest' delight\nin the exquisite stylish daintiness of Plume Under\ngarments.\nYou will find the \"PLUME\" label on a host of\npretty new creations in\nDrawers\nCorset Covers\nCombinations\nUnion Suits\nNovelties\nThere is most surely a mental as well as a physical charm enjoyed by the woman who wears fine under\nthings.\n\u2014Lingerie Section, Second floor\nRugs and Other Floor Cov\nerings Take Lowered Price\nAxminster Rugs\nFour (4) only in this group, 9x12 size, regular\n$65.00. Half Price $32.50\nOne (1) only, 9x12 size, regular $74.00. Half\nPrice $37.00\n25% DISCOUNT ON BALANCE OF OUR STOCK\nOF AXMINSTER RUGS.\nSeamless Velvet Rugs\nTwo (2) only, 9x12 size, regular $74.00, Half\nPrice $37.00\n25% DISCOUNT ON THE BALANCE OF OUR\nSTOCK OF VELVET RUGS.\nSeamless Brussells Rugs\nOur complete stock of Tapestry Brussels rugs\nat a reduction of one-third (1-3) off the regular\nprices.\nFour grades to choose from. Regular prices\n$32.50, $42.50, $59.00 and $67.50\u2014from which you\ndeduct one-third (1-3) for the price J\u00ab*l pay tomor\nrow.\n15% DISCOUNT ON ALL WILTON RUGS\nFrench Wiltons\nHardwick Wiltons\nBundhar Wiltons\nOakdale Wiltons\nCongoleum and Cotta-Lap Rugs\nRepriced\nWhich includes\u2014\nSize 4i/ 2 x4i/ 2 regular $2.75 repriced at $1.90\nSize 3x6 regular $3.50; repriced at $2.75\nSize 3x4 Va\u00bb regular $2.75; repriced at $1.90\nSize 24 in. x 36 in. regular $1.25 repriced at 75^\nSize 18 in. x 27 in. regular 75c; repriced at 45f>\nRoom Size Congoleum Rugs Half Price\nA few Congoleum Rugs, room sizes, slightlv dam\naged in shipping.\nSize 9x12 regular $21.00 Half Price. .$10.50\nSize 9x10.6, regular $19.00; Half Price $9.50\n\u2014Rug Section, Second Floor\nHouse Blooming Bulbs\nGUARANTEED TO BLOOM IN ANY ORDINARY LIVING\nROOM.\nHere is something interesting for the lover of flow\ners in the home.\nNARCISSUS, TULIP, HYACINTH and CROCUS bulbs\nthat are guaranteed to bloom, under ordinary conditions, in\nyour living room.\nIt is a fascinating sight, to watch these bulbs unfold\ntheir leaves and beautiful flowers, especially so when the\nwintry winds blow outside. They bring good cheer to the\nhome in winter.\nComplete assortment of colors. Come early for choice\nselections.\n\u2014Toilet Goods Section, Main Floor\nPoise, Comfort and a Well Dressed\nAppearance Are the Rewards of\nGood Judgment in Choosing a\nCorset\nIf women were compelled to choose a corset by name,\nno doubt their thought, like those of our returning\nheroes from France, would be\u2014\"American Lady.\"\n\"American Lady\" corsets\nin the new spring models,\nflesh tint materials, top\nless styles are priced at\n$2.75 $3\n\"American Lady\" brocad\ned models are also flesh\ntinted and topless styles.\nPriced at\n$4.50\u2014 $5\n\"American Lady\" Corsets\nor a fine quality pink sat\nin, showing many of the\nfavored medium tops,\nboned with \"mightybone\"\na special of American\nLady corsets. Prices\n$3.95, $5.00\nand\n\u2014Corset Section, Second Floor.\n$6.00\nTomorrow There Is the Dawn of a\n25% Reduction on All Men's Hats\n\u00f6 m 'ijWIKSMN\nmm","height":"23064","width":"19272"}}
